"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77669","Home Office","false","2014-07-25","<p>In 2013, Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO) received 1,123 written enquiries from Members of both Houses and 813 telephone enquiries via the 'MP's hotline' service. In the first six months of 2014, HMPO has received 1, 394 written enquiries and 13, 906 telephone enquiries.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-25T16:51:39.7772642Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77669/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77669/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-14","HM Passport Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many enquiries HM Passport Office has received from hon. Members in each of the previous 18 months.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77670","Home Office","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO) does not collect information on <br>compensation in the format requested. Performance data is not collected at <br>these levels. HMPO monitors perfermance at national level as it re-distributes<br>work across the UK estate to manage any variation in local levels of passport demand.<br>The cost of identifying information in the format requested would be disproportionate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-22T14:38:38.292888Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77670/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77670/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-14","Passports: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applicants resident in (a) Preston constituency and (b) Lancashire have been compensated by HM Passport Service in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77671","Home Office","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Passport Office (HMPO) does not collect information on <br>compensation in the format requested. Performance data is not collected at <br>these levels. HMPO monitors perfermance at national level as it re-distributes<br>work across the UK estate to manage any variation in local levels of passport demand.<br>The cost of identifying information in the format requested would be disproportionate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-22T14:39:18.8852936Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77671/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77671/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-14","Passports: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport renewals for residents in (a) Preston constituency and (b) Lancashire have been completed within three weeks from receipt in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77672","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-30","<p>Information held centrally by the Ministry of Justice on cracked trial hearings does not include details regarding the occupation of absent witnesses. It is not possible to separately identify trials which crack due to police officers failing to attend court as witnesses. On the occasions when non-attendance of a police officer is the cause, we would expect the prosecutor to raise the matter with the Police force in question. Issues with police witness non-attendance should be discussed by the relevant Local Criminal Justice Board as part of their performance discussions.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-30T15:25:34.2326852Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77672/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77672/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Police: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken to tackle trials cracking due to police officers failing to attend court as witnesses.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77673","Home Office","false","2014-07-30","<p>As part of the Home Office transparency programme, any spend over £25,000 is available on the Department’s website. Since January 2011, all contracts over £10,000 in value are published on Contracts Finder (<a href="http://www.contractsfinder.co.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.contractsfinder.co.uk/</a>).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-30T12:41:53.1500704Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77673/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77673/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-14","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department paid to (a) G4S, (b) Serco, (c) Sodexo, (d) GEOAmey, (e) Capita, (f) Atos, (g) Mitie, (h) Working Links, (i) A4E, (j) MTC Amey, (k) GEO Group and (l) Carillion in (i) 2010-11, (ii) 2011-12, (iii) 2012-13 and (iv) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77674","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-18","<p>Information held on the prison population in England and Wales includes summary details of the main offences committed by prisoners, however it does not include specific information in relation to the professions of offenders on conviction. This detailed information may be held on individual prisoner files for offender management purposes.</p><p> </p><p>In order to provide data relating to the number of offenders serving prison sentences and the criminal offences committed whilst serving as police officers would involve manually examining prisoner records which could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-18T11:12:09.4746495Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77674/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77674/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Police: Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people are serving prison sentences for crimes committed whilst serving as police officers in England and Wales; for what crimes those people were imprisoned and by which police force they were employed before conviction.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77675","Home Office","false","2014-08-11","<p>To date all but one additional member of staff has been redeployed from within Her Majesty's (HMPO) Passport Office and the wider Home Office. Over 650 staff have been redeployed to HMPO frontline services since January 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-08-11T15:35:38.293106Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77675/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77675/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-14","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the viability of civil servants from other Departments being deployed to assist in the processing of outstanding passport applications.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","205644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77676","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-17","<p> </p><p>Public protection is at the heart of our Transforming Rehabilitation reforms. The new National Probation Service is responsible for the direct management of those offenders who pose the highest risk of serious harm to the public and who have committed the most serious offences. Offenders who are deemed to pose a medium and low risk are being managed by a Community Rehabilitation Company. Every offender will be risk assessed prior to allocation to any probation provider and also upon leaving prison; this will be reviewed when there are indicators that their risk of serious harm to the public has increased to high.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These questions have been answered using the Ministry of Justice’s published proven re-offending statistics for England and Wales, broken down further by police force area. These statistics are published on a quarterly basis and the latest bulletin on a calendar year basis was published on 31 October 2013. Please note that 2011 is the latest full calendar year for which data are available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table 1 presents the one year proven re-offending rates for all adult and juvenile offenders in England and Wales, by police force area, for each year from 2007 to 2011.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table 2 presents the one year proven re-offending rates for all adult and juvenile offenders cautioned or convicted of sexual offences in England and Wales, by police force area, for each year from 2007 to 2011.</p><p> </p><p>A proven re-offence is defined as any offence committed in a one year follow-up period and receiving a court conviction, caution, reprimand or warning in the one year follow-up. Following this one year period, a further six month waiting period is allowed for cases to progress through the courts.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A large part of the variability in the re-offending rates presented in Tables 1 and 2 reflects the mix of offenders within each Police Force Area and, therefore, comparisons between Police Force Areas should not be made using these raw re-offending rates.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of these tables has been placed in the Library.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","205706","2014-09-17T14:03:42.5907666Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77676/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77676/answer","Re-offending rates by police force area 2007 - 2011.xls","Tables: Re-offending rates by police force area","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77676/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Sexual Offences: Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the reoffending rate was for sex offenders in England and Wales by police force area in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","205707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77677","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-17","<p> </p><p>Public protection is at the heart of our Transforming Rehabilitation reforms. The new National Probation Service is responsible for the direct management of those offenders who pose the highest risk of serious harm to the public and who have committed the most serious offences. Offenders who are deemed to pose a medium and low risk are being managed by a Community Rehabilitation Company. Every offender will be risk assessed prior to allocation to any probation provider and also upon leaving prison; this will be reviewed when there are indicators that their risk of serious harm to the public has increased to high.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These questions have been answered using the Ministry of Justice’s published proven re-offending statistics for England and Wales, broken down further by police force area. These statistics are published on a quarterly basis and the latest bulletin on a calendar year basis was published on 31 October 2013. Please note that 2011 is the latest full calendar year for which data are available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table 1 presents the one year proven re-offending rates for all adult and juvenile offenders in England and Wales, by police force area, for each year from 2007 to 2011.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table 2 presents the one year proven re-offending rates for all adult and juvenile offenders cautioned or convicted of sexual offences in England and Wales, by police force area, for each year from 2007 to 2011.</p><p> </p><p>A proven re-offence is defined as any offence committed in a one year follow-up period and receiving a court conviction, caution, reprimand or warning in the one year follow-up. Following this one year period, a further six month waiting period is allowed for cases to progress through the courts.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A large part of the variability in the re-offending rates presented in Tables 1 and 2 reflects the mix of