"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77690","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-22","<p>678 staff in the House of Commons have remained at the same pay band since 2010 and received a pay rise. These pay increases varied depending on factors including where the person fell in the pay band and length of service. Increases fell within the following ranges:</p><ul><li>£73 – £8,388 in the A–E pay bands (520 people);</li><li>£120 – £380 in the Catering Service (134), and</li><li>£318 – £1,230 in the Senior Commons Structure (24).</li></ul>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-22T10:42:49.9944243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77690/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77690/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-14","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, how many officials employed by the House of Commons, of each grade, have remained at that grade since 2010 but received a pay rise; and how much of a rise each such person at each such grade has received.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","205460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77691","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>The number of DFID staff who have remained in the same grade since 2010, but have received a pay rise is set out below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Grade</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>AA</strong></p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>AO</strong></p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>EO</strong></p></td><td><p>48</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>HEO</strong></p></td><td><p>55</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>SEO</strong></p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>G7</strong></p></td><td><p>91</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>G6</strong></p></td><td><p>84</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>SCS</strong></p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>378</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government announced a pay freeze in 2010 which meant that all pay scales for DFID were frozen for two years (2011 and 2012) except for those earning less than the full time equivalent of £21,000. In 2013 and 2014 increases to pay scales were restricted to an average 1% cost of living increase.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All staff below the SCS within DFID have a contractual right to pay progression. Throughout the period from 2010 those staff not at the top of their pay range received an annual incremental increase.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-21T16:30:45.391547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77691/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77691/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many officials employed by her Department, of each grade, have remained at that grade since 2010 but received a pay rise; and how much of a rise each such person at each such grade has received.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","205461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77692","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>DFID has not released any land for the purpose of building new homes since May 2010.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-21T11:53:03.9861067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77692/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77692/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much land her Department has released for the purpose of building new homes since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","205482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77693","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>The UK supports a post-2015 target on universal health coverage. This language is included in the most recent draft goals and targets list released by the co-chairs of the Open Working Group (OWG) on 2 June.</p><p> </p><p>The final targets in the post-2015 development framework will be subject to international negotiations in the United Nations, in which the UK will play an active role.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-17T16:04:56.6379431Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77693/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77693/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Developing Countries: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will support the inclusion of universal health coverage in the goal on health in the Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","205607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77694","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>The UK, through our Troika, have made statements in the Open Working Group on Sustainable Development Goals on the importance of “leaving no one behind” as an overarching principle for the post 2015 framework.</p><p> </p><p>The final goals and targets in the post-2015 development framework will be subject to international negotiations in the United Nations, in which the UK will play an active role.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-17T16:05:28.1460338Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77694/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77694/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the report of the High Level panel of Eminent Persons on the Post-2015 Development Agenda, what steps she is taking to ensure that the pledge to leave no-one behind is effectively translated into the target language of the proposed Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","205608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77695","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>Assessments are still underway as to the extent of any damage to UK or EU funded projects.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-21T12:48:32.972381Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77695/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77695/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what reports she has received on projects in Gaza funded by (a) her Department and (b) the EU which have been damaged or destroyed by Israeli military hardware in July 2014; and what representations she has made to the Israeli government on this matter.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","205493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77696","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p>DFID's development programming is concerned with extreme poverty everywhere, but the Department focuses its financial investments on poor people in countries where extreme poverty is currently a problem, with relatively weak future prospects of the poor, and for which a self-financed exit from poverty is not feasible at this stage.</p><p>DFID has 28 priority countries, fourteen of which are Commonwealth countries. The UK is committed to its strong relationships with the countries of the Commonwealth and in the financial year 2013-14, approximately one third of the Department's bilateral expenditure went to Commonwealth countries. These figures exclude the UK Government's contribution to multilateral organisations and regional programmes which also benefit Commonwealth countries.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-17T14:26:38.0749346Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77696/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77696/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will takes steps to adapt her Department's budget to favour Commonwealth countries.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","205529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77697","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>The UK supports a target to hold the increase in global average temperature below a 2°C rise in accordance with international agreements.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The final targets in the post-2015 development framework will however be subject to international negotiations in the United Nations, in which the UK will play an active role.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-17T16:05:48.115528Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77697/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77697/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will support the inclusion in the Sustainable Development Goals of a standalone goal on climate change, in addition to targets on environmental sustainability integrated across the framework, accompanied by a measure to keep the rise in global temperatures at 2ºC on pre-industrialisation levels.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","205609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77698","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>The UK supports a target to reduce the number of people living on less than $1.25 a day and a target on reducing poverty according to national definitions. This language is included in the most recent draft goals and targets list released by the co-chairs of the Open Working Group (OWG) on 2 June.</p><p> </p><p>The final targets in the post-2015 development framework will however be subject to international negotiations in the United Nations, in which the UK will play an active role.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-17T16:06:23.0274174Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77698/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77698/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-14","Developing Countries: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will support the inclusion in the Sustainable Development Goals of a target on reducing the number of people living on less than $2 a day under the goal on poverty.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Murphy","East Renfrewshire","Mr Jim Murphy","205610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77699","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-22","<p>It has not been possible to answer this question within the allotted timeframe. I will write to the Rt. Hon member.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-07-22T16:39:57.9168729Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77699/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77699/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Prisons: Civil Disorder","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times the National Tactical Response Group (NTRG) was called out in each month in 2014 to date; and to which prison the NTRG was called out in each case.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77700","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-22","<p>It has not been possible to answer this question within the allotted timeframe. I will write to the Rt. Hon member.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","205490","2014-07-22T16:42:38.0692965Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77700/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77700/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","National Offender Management Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much the National Offender Management Service has spent on (a) temporary and (b) agency staff in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012, (iv) 2013 and (v) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77701","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>Information held centrally by the Ministry of Justice on cracked trial hearings does not include details regarding the occupation of absent witnesses. It is not possible to separately identify trials which crack due to police officers failing to attend court as witnesses. This information could only be obtained from the individual courts at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T12:44:32.0475561Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77701/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77701/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Police: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many trials in each magistrates' court in Lancashire cracked due to failure of police officers to attend court as witnesses between 1 January 2013 and 30 June 2014.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77702","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>The number of offenders sentenced to immediate custody for non-payment of fines by each magistrates’ court in Lancashire is not available from information held centrally by the Ministry of Justice on the Court Proceedings Database. In order to provide this information it would involve the manual checking of case files and to do so would be disproportionate to costs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>HMCTS takes the issue of fine enforcement very seriously and is working to ensure that clamping down on fine defaulters is a continued priority nationwide. The courts have a range of powers to enforce payment of fines, including the use of bailiffs to seize goods, and deductions from earnings or benefits. Ultimately, an offender can be imprisoned for non-payment of their fine.</p><p> </p><p>Over recent years we have overseen improvements to the collection of financial penalties. There was a total of £290m collected against fines and related impositions in 2013/14 which was a record high.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T15:19:29.1835751Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77702/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77702/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Fines: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were given a term of imprisonment by each magistrates' court in Lancashire for non-payment of fines in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77703","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-22","<p>Information held centrally by the Ministry of Justice on cracked trial hearings does not include details regarding the occupation of absent witnesses. It is not possible to separately identify trials which crack due to police officers failing to attend court as witnesses. On the occasions when non-attendance of a police officer is the cause, we would expect the prosecutor to raise the matter with the Police force in question. Issues with police witness non-attendance should be discussed by the relevant Local Criminal Justice Board as part of their performance discussions.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-22T16:47:48.8835624Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77703/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77703/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Police: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department has taken to tackle trials cracking due to non-attendance of police officers as witnesses.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","205669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77704","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-22","<p>There are no central records of the number of prisoners who have self-declared a transgender status.</p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes","205542","2014-07-22T15:36:18.1590682Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77704/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77704/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Prisoners: Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many female born prisoners have self-declared transgender status since 2011.","false","Biography information for Nick de Bois","Enfield North","Nick de Bois","205537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77705","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>Prisons will be assessed as having achieved ‘Steady State’ when they are delivering the recommended benchmark ‘core day’, staffing profiles and regime, in compliance with arrangements formally agreed with Trades Unions.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T13:03:48.5574681Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77705/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77705/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Prisons: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2014, Official Report, column 396W, on prisons: business, what criteria each prison has to meet to be considered to have achieved Steady State.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77706","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>Prison is the right place for serious, dangerous and persistent offenders. Since 2010, those who break the law are more likely to be sent to prison.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last ten years the number of prisoners in England and Wales aged 60 and over has risen each year. The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) is working hard to ensure that prisons are equipped to meet the needs of this group, including through the commissioning of health and social care services.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The table below shows the population of prisoners by specified age groups in all prison establishments in England and Wales, from the most recent available data at the end of March 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Providing information on a single individual that is personal and potentially disclosive, such as the age of the oldest prisoner in England and Wales, would be contrary to our obligations under the Data Protection Act 1998. There were, however, five prisoners aged 90 or over as of 31 March 2014.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="7">Table 1: Prison population aged 60 and over, by age group, England and Wales, 31 March 2014.</td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>Age</strong></td><td><strong>31-Mar-14</strong></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>60-65</td><td>1,791</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>66-70</td><td>967</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>71-75</td><td>489</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>76-80</td><td>228</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td>Over age 80</td><td>102</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total aged 60 and over</strong></td><td><strong>3,577</strong></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><strong>Data Sources and Quality</strong><br>These figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","205507","2014-07-21T12:53:46.4903926Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77706/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77706/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-14","Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how old the oldest prison inmate in England and Wales is.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205506"
